{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:32:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18187"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18187"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.1,0.57,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79288"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10901"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64610"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7173"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25348"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79288"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following dermatomes is responsible for sensation at the posterior aspect of the heel?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["L2","L3","L4","S1","S2"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior aspect of the heel is innervated by the \u003Cstrong\u003ES1\u003C/strong\u003E dermatome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EL2\u003C/strong\u003E dermatome covers the upper anterior thigh, while the \u003Cstrong\u003EL3\u003C/strong\u003E dermatome covers the lower anterior thigh and knee region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EL4\u003C/strong\u003E dermatome includes the medial aspect of the leg and foot, particularly the medial malleolus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003ES2\u003C/strong\u003E dermatome covers the posterior thigh and upper calf, but not the heel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding dermatomes is essential for localising neurological lesions and guiding further investigations and management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The S1 dermatome covers the posterior aspect of the heel.","Dermatomes are areas of skin innervated by sensory fibers from a single spinal nerve root.","Understanding dermatomes is crucial for diagnosing and managing neurological conditions."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64610"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18187"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},